The Chronicle Bongani Ndlovu, Showbiz Correspondent BIGGER and better is what was promised and this was what was delivered during the Roil Bulawayo Arts Awards held at the Zimbabwe International Exhibition Centre on Saturday evening. <img class="alignnone wp-image-455648" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/06/0M9A0426-360x212.png" alt="" width="671" height="395" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/06/0M9A0426-360x212.png 360w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/06/0M9A0426.png 680w" sizes="(max-width: 671px) 100vw, 671px" /> Touted as the biggest dress up event in the city, the who’s who in Bulawayo came out in droves wearing outlandish, jaw dropping and statement making outfits and brought the city to a standstill. <img class="alignnone  wp-image-455668" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/07/0M9A0340-360x201.png" alt="" width="672" height="375" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/07/0M9A0340-360x200.png 360w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/07/0M9A0340.png 680w" sizes="(max-width: 672px) 100vw, 672px" /> The red carpet was the centre of attraction where the fashion police scrutinised what each person was wearing. <img class="alignnone wp-image-455649" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/06/0M9A0473-360x201.png" alt="" width="670" height="374" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/06/0M9A0473-360x200.png 360w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/06/0M9A0473.png 680w" sizes="(max-width: 670px) 100vw, 670px" /> However, this was a precursor of what was going to happen during the night. The huge venue, although not filled to the brim, was teeming with excitement and great performances on stage. Artistes in their varied ensembles and individually never put a foot wrong as they made it their mission to entertain the crowd. <img class="alignnone  wp-image-455666" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/07/0M9A0483-360x201.png" alt="" width="670" height="374" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/07/0M9A0483-360x200.png 360w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/07/0M9A0483.png 680w" sizes="(max-width: 670px) 100vw, 670px" /> The awards were graced by the Minister of Industry and Commerce Mangaliso Ndlovu, National Arts Council of Zimbabwe chairperson Nicholas Moyo and United Refineries CEO Busisa Moyo among other dignitaries. <img class="alignnone wp-image-455650" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/06/0M9A0435-360x201.png" alt="" width="672" height="375" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/06/0M9A0435-360x200.png 360w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/06/0M9A0435.png 680w" sizes="(max-width: 672px) 100vw, 672px" /> On the winners front, the highlight was Novuyo-Seagirl who won Song of the Year for her track AEIOU and Outstanding Female Artiste, while Iyasa made a clean sweep of the dance awards winning the Outstanding Male dancer, Female dancer and Arts ensemble award. Filmmaker Daniel Lasker walked away with two gongs Outstanding TV/Film director and Outstanding Film for the short movie The Man. <img class="alignnone wp-image-455651" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/06/0M9A0440-360x201.png" alt="" width="670" height="374" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/06/0M9A0440-360x200.png 360w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/06/0M9A0440.png 680w" sizes="(max-width: 670px) 100vw, 670px" /> Cal Vin won the Outstanding Male Artiste award while Asaph, who had a trailblazing 2018, was crowned hip hop king for the second year running at the awards. <img class="alignnone  wp-image-455669" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/07/0M9A0423-360x201.png" alt="" width="670" height="374" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/07/0M9A0423-360x200.png 360w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/07/0M9A0423.png 680w" sizes="(max-width: 670px) 100vw, 670px" /> A first happened; there was a tie in the Outstanding Actor in theatre award where Cedrick Msongelwa and Ronald Sigeca (Zandezi) could not be separated. <img class="alignnone wp-image-455654" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/06/0M9A0441-360x201.png" alt="" width="670" height="374" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/06/0M9A0441-360x200.png 360w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/06/0M9A0441.png 680w" sizes="(max-width: 670px) 100vw, 670px" /> In the category that caused much controversy after Oskido rejected the nomination, Outstanding Arts Personality from Outside of Bulawayo, Winky D walked away with the gong. <img class="alignnone wp-image-455657" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/06/0M9A0459-360x201.png" alt="" width="670" height="374" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/06/0M9A0459-360x200.png 360w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/06/0M9A0459.png 680w" sizes="(max-width: 670px) 100vw, 670px" /> It was also befitting that the awards, which are a celebration of arts efforts, awarded Lovemore Majaivana a Lifetime Achievement award. This is a man whose music has been in the social fabric of the city and even the country for eternity. Below is the full list of winner at the awards. ROIL BULAWAYO ARTS AWARDS WINNERS LIST (2019) MUSIC AWARDS 1. Outstanding Gospel Artist/Act – Knowledge Nkiwane 2. Outstanding Kwaito/House/Gqom Artist/Act – Skaiva 3. Outstanding Tshibilika/Rhumba Artist/Act – Clement Magwaza 4. Outstanding Imbube/Accapella Act – Nobuntu 5. Outstanding Alternative (Maskandi/Jazz) Music Artist – Jeys Marabini 6. Outstanding Hip Hop Artist/Act – Asaph 7. Outstanding Female Artist – Novuyo Seagirl 8. Outstanding Male Artist – Cal vin 9. Song of the Year – A. E. I. O. U. by Novuyo Seagirl 10. Outstanding Music Producer – Percy Mativenga 11. Outstanding Video Director – Vusa “Blaqs” Hlatshwayo 12. Outstanding Choral Group – Bulawayo Choristers DANCE AWARDS 13. Outstanding Male Dancer – Newman Gondwe (IYASA) 14. Outstanding Female Dancer – Lethokuhle Ncube (IYASA) 15. Outstanding Contemporary Dance Ensemble – IYASA 16. Outstanding Traditional Dance Ensemble – Umkhathi Theatre Works THEATRE
AWARDS 17. Outstanding Theatre Production – Zandezi 18. Outstanding Theatre Actress – Charlene Mangweni (Ukama) 19. Outstanding Theatre Actor – Cadrick Msongelwa & Ronald Sigeca (Zandezi) 20. Outstanding Director – Memory Kumbota (Garden of Dreams) SCHOOLS
AWARDS 21. Outstanding Arts Educator – Bridget Sayers (Gifford High School) 22. Outstanding Schools Arts Effort (High Schools) – Gifford High School 23. Outstanding Actor (High Schools) – Bruce Gandiyaru (Nketa High School) 24. Outstanding Schools Arts Effort (Primary Schools) – Matshayisikhova Primary School VISUAL
ARTS
AWARDS 25. Outstanding Visual Artist (3 Dimensional) – Sikhulile Sibanda (Ngibuhlungu) 26. Outstanding Visual Artist (2 Dimensional) – George Masarira (Inkululeko) MEDIA
AWARDS 27. Outstanding Arts Photographer – Mgcini Nyoni (ConvergenceZw) 28. Outstanding Arts Journalist Across Board – Bruce Ndlovu (Sunday News) 29. Outstanding Main Stream Media House – Skyz Metro FM 30. Outstanding Online Media – Urban Culxure FILM
